## Stop 2 — Demand

Once you see how each system is built, the next question is who is actually 
using it and when. This is where the data starts telling a story, and also 
where the limits of what Tokyo is willing to share become impossible to 
ignore.

On the BMT, the MTA publishes hourly ridership for every station complex. 
What that data shows is a system shaped almost entirely by the commute: 
demand builds sharply into the 8am rush, collapses through midday, spikes 
again at 5pm, and drops off steeply after. Weekends are a different system 
entirely, with lower overall volume, a later peak around noon, and a much 
flatter curve as commuters give way to leisure riders.


```{r stop2_peak}

peak_hours <- c(8, 17)

y_top <- max(df$p90, na.rm = TRUE) * 1.02

p <- ggplot(df, aes(hour, avg_riders, color = day_type, fill = day_type)) +
  geom_ribbon(aes(ymin = p10, ymax = p90), alpha = 0.18, color = NA) +
  geom_line(linewidth = 1.2) +
  geom_point(size = 2.4) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = peak_hours, linewidth = 0.9, linetype = "dashed", color = mta_blue) +
  geom_text(
    data = tibble(hour = peak_hours),
    aes(x = hour, y = y_top, label = "Rush hour"),
    inherit.aes = FALSE, color = mta_blue, fontface = "bold", vjust = 0, size = 3.6
  ) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 0:23) +
  scale_y_continuous(
    labels = label_number(scale = 1e-3, suffix = "K"),
    expand = expansion(mult = c(0, 0.10))
  ) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c(Weekday = mta_blue, Weekend = mta_orange)) +
  scale_fill_manual(values  = c(Weekday = mta_blue, Weekend = mta_orange)) +
  labs(
    title = "BMT Rush Hour 2025 (average riders by hour)",
    x = "Hour of day",
    y = "Average riders",
    color = NULL, fill = NULL
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 12) +
  theme(
    panel.grid = element_blank(),
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
    axis.line = element_line(color = "gray30", linewidth = 0.6),
    axis.ticks = element_line(color = "gray30"),
    legend.position = "right"
  )

g <- ggplotly(p, tooltip = c("x", "y", "color")) %>%
  layout(
    legend = list(orientation = "v", x = 1.02, y = 0.5, xanchor = "left", yanchor = "middle"),
    margin = list(r = 140),
    hovermode = "closest"
  )

for (i in seq_along(g$x$data)) {
  g$x$data[[i]]$hoverinfo <- "skip"
  g$x$data[[i]]$hovertemplate <- NULL
}

for (i in seq_along(g$x$data)) {
  tr <- g$x$data[[i]]
  if (!is.null(tr$mode) && grepl("markers", tr$mode) &&
      !is.null(tr$name) && tr$name %in% c("Weekday","Weekend")) {
    tr$text <- paste0("Hour of Day: ", tr$x, "<br>Average Riders: ", fmtN(tr$y))
    tr$hoverinfo <- "text"
    tr$hovertemplate <- "%{text}<extra></extra>"
    g$x$data[[i]] <- tr
  }
}

add_band_hover <- function(g, d, which = c("p10","p90"), label) {
  ycol <- which[1]
  g %>% add_trace(
    data = d,
    x = ~hour, y = as.formula(paste0("~", ycol)),
    type = "scatter", mode = "markers",
    marker = list(opacity = 0, size = 12),
    inherit = FALSE, showlegend = FALSE,
    hovertemplate = ~paste0(
      "Hour of Day: ", hour,
      "<br>", label, ": ", fmtN(.data[[ycol]]),
      "<extra></extra>"
    )
  )
}

for (dt in c("Weekday","Weekend")) {
  dsub <- df %>% filter(day_type == dt) %>% arrange(hour)
  g <- add_band_hover(g, dsub, which = "p10", label = "Low Band (10th%)")
  g <- add_band_hover(g, dsub, which = "p90", label = "High Band (90th%)")
}

shown <- character(0)
for (i in seq_along(g$x$data)) {
  nm <- trimws(ifelse(is.null(g$x$data[[i]]$name), "", g$x$data[[i]]$name))
  g$x$data[[i]]$showlegend <- FALSE
  if (nm %in% c("Weekday","Weekend") && !(nm %in% shown)) {
    g$x$data[[i]]$showlegend <- TRUE
    shown <- c(shown, nm)
  }
}

g %>% config(displayModeBar = FALSE)
```
*Average BMT ridership by hour of day, split by day type. The shaded bands 
show the 10th to 90th percentile range across individual days. The shape 
of the curve is consistent, but the volume varies day to day. The commute 
signature is unmistakable. Data: MTA Open Data, 2025.*


## Yamanote Station Demand
For the Yamanote, JR East does not publish hourly ridership publicly. What 
they do publish is annual daily average boardings per station, and those 
numbers alone tell a significant story. Shinjuku handles over 666,000 daily 
boardings in the fiscal year of 2024, making it one of the busiest train stations in the 
world. The top 12 stations on the loop collectively move more people per day 
than many entire transit systems. Every single Yamanote station grew 
year-over-year from FY2023 to FY2024, continuing Tokyo's post-COVID 
recovery across the board.

::: panel-tabset
