::: {.callout-tip appearance="minimal" icon="false"}
Three things stand out when you put BMT and Yamanote demand side by side:

- BMT demand concentrates sharply at 8am and 5pm on 
  weekdays. The Yamanote's loop design means there is no single choke point 
  forcing everyone in the same direction at the same time, so demand spreads 
  more evenly across the day.
- BMT weekend ridership drops noticeably and peaks 
  later around noon. The Yamanote's mix of commuters, tourists, and leisure 
  riders keeps major hubs like Shibuya and Shinjuku high-volume across the 
  full week.
- NYC gives you hourly ridership. Tokyo gives you annual 
  station totals. The Yamanote frequency charts in the next section use 
  scheduled departures as a supply-side stand-in, the best available measure 
  given what JR East actually publishes. That substitution is documented, 
  not hidden.
:::

## Stop 3 — Frequency

Demand tells you who shows up. Frequency tells you what happens when they 
get to the platform, and this is where the structural difference between 
a branching network and a closed loop becomes most concrete.

On the BMT, the MTA scales service to match demand. More trains during rush 
hours, fewer overnight, a step down on weekends compared to weekdays. That 
is a rational approach to running a complex multi-line system, but it means 
riders feel the difference. Waiting four minutes at 8:30am versus twelve 
minutes at 10am is not just an inconvenience. It changes how you plan your 
day and how much margin you have when something goes wrong.


```{r stop3_frequency}

mta_blue   <- "#0039A6"
mta_orange <- "#FF6319"

# Rush-hour markers 
rush_lines <- c(8, 17)

wk <- readr::read_csv("data/mta/bmt_trips_by_hour_weekday.csv", show_col_types = FALSE) %>%
  mutate(day_type = "Weekday")
we <- readr::read_csv("data/mta/bmt_trips_by_hour_weekend.csv", show_col_types = FALSE) %>%
  mutate(day_type = "Weekend")

tot <- bind_rows(wk, we) %>%
  group_by(day_type, hour_service) %>%
  summarize(trips = sum(trips, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop") %>%
  filter(hour_service <= 23) %>%
  mutate(
    day_phrase = if_else(day_type == "Weekend", "On weekends", "On weekdays"),
    se = sqrt(pmax(trips, 1)),
    lo = pmax(trips - 1.2 * se, 0),
    hi = trips + 1.2 * se,
    hover_text = paste0(
      day_phrase, ", in hour ", hour_service,
      ", there are ", trips, " trips scheduled."
    )
  )

wk_df <- tot %>% filter(day_type == "Weekday")
we_df <- tot %>% filter(day_type == "Weekend")

y_top <- max(tot$hi, na.rm = TRUE) * 1.02

peaks <- tot %>%
  group_by(day_type) %>%
  slice_max(trips, n = 1, with_ties = FALSE) %>%
  ungroup()

p <- ggplot(tot, aes(hour_service, trips, color = day_type, group = day_type, text = hover_text)) +

  geom_ribbon(
    data = wk_df,
    aes(x = hour_service, ymin = lo, ymax = hi),
    inherit.aes = FALSE,
    fill = mta_blue, alpha = 0.15
  ) +
  geom_ribbon(
    data = we_df,
    aes(x = hour_service, ymin = lo, ymax = hi),
    inherit.aes = FALSE,
    fill = mta_orange, alpha = 0.15
  ) +
  geom_line(linewidth = 1.4) +
  geom_point(size = 2.4) +
  geom_point(
    data = peaks,
    aes(hour_service, trips, group = day_type),
    inherit.aes = FALSE,
    size = 4.6,
    shape = 21,
    stroke = 1.6,
    fill = "white",
    color = "gray20"
  ) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = rush_lines, linetype = "dashed", linewidth = 0.9, alpha = 0.9) +
  annotate(
    "text",
    x = rush_lines, y = y_top,
    label = "Rush hour",
    vjust = 0, size = 3.5, fontface = "bold", color = mta_blue
  ) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c(Weekday = mta_blue, Weekend = mta_orange)) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 0:23, limits = c(0, 23)) +
  labs(
    title = "Stop 3 — Frequency (BMT total service by hour)",
    subtitle = "Lines show scheduled trips/hour. Shaded band is a visual range (schedule-based).",
    x = "Service hour",
    y = "Total scheduled trip starts",
    color = NULL
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 12) +
  theme(
    panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    axis.line = element_line(color = "gray30", linewidth = 0.6),
    axis.ticks = element_line(color = "gray30"),
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
    legend.position = "top"
  )

ggplotly(p, tooltip = "text") %>%
  layout(
    hovermode = "closest",
    xaxis = list(showgrid = FALSE, fixedrange = TRUE, zeroline = FALSE),
    yaxis = list(showgrid = FALSE, fixedrange = TRUE, zeroline = FALSE)
  ) %>%
  config(displayModeBar = FALSE, scrollZoom = FALSE, doubleClick = FALSE)
```
*BMT scheduled trips per hour by day type. The system throttles up and down 
in direct response to demand. The gap between weekday peaks and weekend 
shoulders is the cost of running a branching network that has to balance 
service across eight lines sharing the same infrastructure. Data: MTA GTFS 
static schedule files.*


The Yamanote barely moves. From early morning through late evening on 
weekdays, trains arrive every three to four minutes. Many Tokyo commuters 
do not check a schedule. They walk to the platform.


